In the documentation for [Slide&#39;s children prop](https://material-ui.com/api/slide/#props) you can find:

&gt; A single child content element.
&gt;
&gt; ⚠️ Needs to be able to hold a ref.

`Slide` [uses `React.cloneElement`](https://github.com/mui-org/material-ui/blob/v4.5.0/packages/material-ui/src/Slide/Slide.js#L214) to add a ref and props to the single child. If there are multiple children or if `children` is an array (even if the array contains only one child), then `Slide` will get the error you encountered because `children.props` is not defined and it is trying to reference `children.props.style`.

Below is a little example to just help better understand the cause of the error:

```
import React from &quot;react&quot;;
import ReactDOM from &quot;react-dom&quot;;

const MockSlide = ({ children }) =&gt; {
  if (children.props) {
    return (
      &lt;div&gt;
        {children}
        children.props is defined
      &lt;/div&gt;
    );
  }
  return (
    &lt;div&gt;
      {children}
      children.props is not defined
    &lt;/div&gt;
  );
};
const sectionArray = [
  &quot;An array also causes problems (even if only one element)&quot;
];
function App() {
  return (
    &lt;div className=&quot;App&quot;&gt;
      &lt;MockSlide&gt;
        &lt;div&gt;Single child works fine&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;/MockSlide&gt;
      &lt;br /&gt;
      &lt;br /&gt;
      &lt;MockSlide&gt;
        &lt;div&gt;Multiple children&lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;div&gt;causes problems with Slide&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;/MockSlide&gt;
      &lt;br /&gt;
      &lt;br /&gt;
      &lt;MockSlide&gt;
        {sectionArray.map(section =&gt; {
          return &lt;div&gt;{section}&lt;/div&gt;;
        })}
      &lt;/MockSlide&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  );
}

const rootElement = document.getElementById(&quot;root&quot;);
ReactDOM.render(&lt;App /&gt;, rootElement);
```

[![Edit Slide single child requirement](https://codesandbox.io/static/img/play-codesandbox.svg)](https://codesandbox.io/s/slide-single-child-requirement-knduk?fontsize=14)

One potential solution is to wrap everything inside the `Slide` in a single `&lt;div&gt;` element.

